@node Over "Overview"

@{b}OVERVIEW-------------------------------@{ub}

CompareDirs is a directory compare tool. In other words it allows to
compare files from two directories and tells which are identical,
different, only in one directory.

CompareDirs allows you to compare the directory structure of two
directories and it compares all files, that can be found in both
directories and all subdirectories, byte by byte.

This is very useful for checking a backup of your harddisk on
CD-recordable or another mass storage medium. Since it really
compares all files, that will be output as identical, byte by byte
you can be sure that no error occurred during backing up.

It is also practical to check for differences since the last backup.

And if you have got a new archive of a program you already have,
CompareDirs allows you to check it out for different files.

CompareDirs features are:
    * byte by byte comparison;
    * memory buffer to reduce disk access;
    * shell only mode;
    * Reaction GUI;
    * Locale support;
    * Detect identical files with different dates;
    * Make use of an external File Diff utility to display
      differences between files.

@endnode

@node Requ "System Requirements"

@{b}SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS--------------------@{ub}

CompareDirs have little requirements, those are :
    * AmigaOS 4.x (>= V51.104)
    * AISS
    * that's all :-)

@{b}AISS@{ub}

AISS is a system to provide Amiga applications with consistent icons.
It's developped by Martin "Mason" Merz and available for download on
his website at @{"http://www.masonicons.info/6.html" system "C:URLOpen http://www.masonicons.info/6.html"}.
@endnode

@node Usag "Usage"

@{b}USAGE----------------------------------@{ub}

@{b}CLI Arguments@{ub}

The calling syntax is:

    CompareDirs <DIR1> <DIR2> [<RESULTFILE>][NOIDENT][NOGUI][NOLEFT]
                                [NORIGHT][NODIFFERENT][NOSUBDIR]

or as a argument template:
    @{i}DIR1/A,DIR2/A,RESULTFILE,NOIDENT/S,NOGUI/S,NOLEFT/S,NORIGHT/S,NODIFFERENT/S@{ui}

    DIR1:
           the name of the first directory to compare. It can also be
           referred as the "left directory". This is mandatory.

    DIR2:
           the name of the second directory to compare. It can also be
           referred as the "right directory". This is mandatory.

    RESULTFILE:
           the name of a file where to output the comparison results.
           This argument is only examined when in NOGUI mode. This is
           optional and by default all outputs goes to standard output
           and standard error output streams (i.e. you'll see them in
           the console window). 

    NOIDENT:
           switch allows suppressing output of the identical files. This
           is optional and by default these files are displayed.

    NOGUI:
           this switch allows to start in text mode, i.e. no graphical
           interface will be opened and instead everything will go to
           the console window. This is optional and by default the
           program starts in GUI mode.

    NOLEFT:
           switch allows suppressing output of files only in left directory.
           This is optional and by default these files are displayed.

    NORIGHT:
           switch allows suppressing output of files only in right directory.
           This is optional and by default these files are displayed.

    NODIFFERENT:
           switch allows suppressing output of different files. This is
           optional and by default these files are displayed.

    NOSUBDIR :
           switch preventing scan of subdirectories while comparing the
           given directories.

The text output looks like:


----------------  snip  ----------------

RAM:> CompareDirs DEVS: RAM:devs

Scanning directory DEVS:
Scanning directory RAM:devs
Comparing files
Showing results


Identical files:

 DataTypes/  (0)
 DataTypes/8SVX  (138)
 DataTypes/8SVX.info  (1652)
 DataTypes/ILBM  (138)
 DataTypes/ILBM.info  (1652)
 DOSDrivers.info  (1650)
 DOSDrivers/  (0)
 DOSDrivers/AUX  (118)
 DOSDrivers/AUX.info  (1813)
 mountlist  (4252)
 parallel.device  (4292)
 printer.device  (27420)
 serial.device  (5412)
 system-configuration  (232)


Files only in DEVS: :

 DOSDrivers/PC0  (787)
 DOSDrivers/PC0.info  (1824)
 Mountlist.bak  (4135)


Files only in RAM:devs :

 bla.device  (5712)


Different files:

 clipboard.device  (6944)
 mfm.device  (6780 <-> 3848)

Identical files with updated date:


----------------  snip  ----------------
@endnode

@node Diff "Comparaison de fichiers"

@{b}FILE COMPARISON------------------------@{ub}

@{b}Only in GUI mode@{ub}

When files are present in both directories and are deemed as different
(white cross in a red disc) it's possible to double clic on the row
to open a file diff utility.

By default it uses @{"AMUIDiff.os4" system "C:URLOpen http://os4depot.net/index.php?function=showfile&file=utility/text/misc/amuidiff.lha"} but it's possible to configure it using
the environment variable "CompareDirs/Diff".
This variable must contains the path and name to the software to use and
two "%s" which will be replaced at runtime by both files to examine (the
first holds for the left directory file, the second the right one).

For example using AMUIDiff.os4 and the new AmigaOS 4.1 feature AppDir:

@{fg fill}Setenv CompareDirs/Diff AppDir:AMUIDiff.os4 \"%s\" \"%s\"@{fg text}

@endnode

@node Issu "Known issues and report new ones"

@{b}KNOWN ISSUES AND REPORT NEW ONES-------@{ub}

@{b}Known issues@{ub}

 * Files of size zero are not (and cannot be) compared.
 * Softlinks are treated like files of size zero, what means that
   their contents are not compared.
 * It uses a 1MB memory block for comparing files to reduce disk
   accesses. So you will need at least one MB of contiguous free
   memory to start CompareDirs.

@{b}Report new issues@{ub}

 In the event you are faced to an issue that is not known you are
 welcome to report it to me.
 For this you have at your convenience the possibility to send me 
 an email at @{"alexandre@balaban.fr" system "C:URLOpen mailto:alexandre@balaban.fr?subject=[CompareDirs]"} or you can enter a new issue in
 the CompareDirs's tracker which is kindly hosted by os4depot.net at
 @{"http://bugs.os4depot.net/?function=viewsoftware&softwareid=7" system "C:URLOpen http://bugs.os4depot.net/?function=viewsoftware&softwareid=7"}.
 Please note that you would need to register an account in order to
 report any issue. 
@endnode

